stylometry:
Transportation is when a company ships a product from one destination, to another, with no stops inbetween.  The difference between transportation and transhipment, is that a transshipment problem has stops at warehouses in between Point A and Point B of the trip. 

Nods, arcs, and flows are common factors in transportation and transhipment problems.  A node is a geographical location that is represented by a circle.  An arc is represented by an arrow, and shows the path between nodes.  Finally, a flow is the amount of product that is traveling, and flows always travel on the arrows that are arcs. 

A specific transhipment problem would be if a company was shipping to their customer location, and they needed to hold inventory in process at a warehouse.  Then, using solver, they company would be able to find out the right directional path in order to cost minimize. They would be able to discover which warehouses to store in, and which ones won't be necessary.  This is useful because it will save the company money in the long run by determining which parts are necessary or not.
